{\plain\f4\fs21\b\cf2\ulc2
(257) Definitions. 
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
For the purpose of this chapter the following definitions apply.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“Creative thinking”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
refers to students who have advanced insight, outstanding imagination and innovative reasoning ability. Such students possess outstanding ability to integrate seemingly unrelated information in formulating unique ideas, insights, solutions, or products.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“Department”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
refers to the department of education.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“General intellectual ability”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
refers to students who can learn at a faster pace, master higher levels of content and handle abstract concepts at a significantly higher level than expected, given the student’s chronological age and experiences.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“Gifted and talented children”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
refers to those students, distinguished from the total K-12 student population, who are identified as possessing outstanding ability and who are capable of high performance. Gifted and talented children are children who require appropriate instruction and educational services commensurate with their abilities and needs beyond those provided by the regular school program. Gifted and talented children include those children with demonstrated achievement or potential ability, or both, in any of the following areas or in combination: general intellectual ability, creative thinking, leadership ability, visual and performing arts ability, or specific ability aptitude.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“Leadership ability”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
refers to those students who possess outstanding potential or demonstrated ability to exercise influence on decision making. These students may be consistently recognized by their peers, may demonstrate leadership behavior through school and nonschool activities or may evidence personal skills and abilities that are characteristic of effective leaders.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“Program budget”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
is a budget consisting of a listing of the estimated direct program expenditures, by function and object, that are necessary to accomplish the goals of the program in meeting the needs of identified students, along with a listing of the sources of revenue and, if necessary, the amounts of fund balance to be applied.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“Specific ability aptitude”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
refers to those students who have exceptionally high achievement or potential and a high degree of interest in a specific field of study.
}
\par
\pard\qj\fi340\sl250
{\plain\f4\fs21\i\cf2\ulc2
“Visual or performing arts ability”\~
}
{\plain\f4\fs21\cf2\ulc2
refers to students who demonstrate or indicate potential for outstanding aesthetic production or creativity in areas such as art, dance, music, drama, and media production.
}
